# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# combined — __iand__, __ior__, __ixor__ across all 10 asyncio subjects
#
# Covers the full matrix: 10 classes x 3 methods = 30 rows.
# __iand__: false for all 10 — in-place bitwise AND is not defined.
# __ior__:  false for all 10 — in-place bitwise OR is not defined.
# __ixor__: false for all 10 — in-place bitwise XOR is not defined.
# All 30 values are false.
# asyncio types are designed for coroutine-based concurrency — their entire
#   API surface is expressed through await, async with, async for, and
#   explicit method calls. Neither the forward bitwise logical operators
#   (wave 661: __and__/__or__/__xor__ all false) nor the reflected variants
#   (wave 665: __rand__/__ror__/__rxor__ all false) appear in any asyncio
#   type's __dict__. The in-place variants tested here follow the same pattern.
# asyncio.Event note: Event manages a simple boolean flag (set/clear/wait);
#   it defines no bitwise protocol of any kind, including in-place variants.
# asyncio.Lock/Condition note: mutual-exclusion synchronization objects;
#   augmented bitwise assignment operators have no meaning for lock state.
# asyncio.Semaphore/BoundedSemaphore note: the permit counter is encapsulated
#   and not exposed for any bitwise operation, including &=, |=, ^=.
# asyncio.Queue note: Queue is an ordered item store. Items are managed
#   solely through put()/get() coroutine calls; no bitwise protocol is
#   defined from any side.
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

